[src:golang/context] Package context defines the Context type, which carries deadlines, cancellation signals, and other request-scoped values across API boundaries and between processes.
[src:golang/context] Incoming requests to a server should create a Context, and outgoing calls to servers should accept a Context.
[src:golang/context] The chain of function calls between them must propagate the Context, optionally replacing it with a derived Context created using WithCancel, WithDeadline, WithTimeout, or WithValue.
[src:golang/context] A Context may be canceled to indicate that work done on its behalf should stop.
[src:golang/context] A Context with a deadline is canceled after the deadline passes.
[src:golang/context] When a Context is canceled, all Contexts derived from it are also canceled.
[src:golang/context] The WithCancel, WithDeadline, and WithTimeout functions take a Context (the parent) and return a derived Context (the child) and a CancelFunc.
[src:golang/context] Calling the CancelFunc directly cancels the child and its children, removes the parent's reference to the child, and stops any associated timers.
[src:golang/context] Failing to call the CancelFunc leaks the child and its children until the parent is canceled.
[src:golang/context] The go vet tool checks that CancelFuncs are used on all control-flow paths.
[src:golang/context] The WithCancelCause, WithDeadlineCause, and WithTimeoutCause functions return a CancelCauseFunc, which takes an error and records it as the cancellation cause.
[src:golang/context] Calling Cause on the canceled context or any of its children retrieves the cause.
[src:golang/context] If no cause is specified, Cause(ctx) returns the same value as ctx.Err().
[src:golang/context] Do not store Contexts inside a struct type; instead, pass a Context explicitly to each function that needs it.
[src:golang/context] This is discussed further in https://go.dev/blog/context-and-structs.
[src:golang/context] Do not pass a nil Context, even if a function permits it.
[src:golang/context] Pass context.TODO if you are unsure about which Context to use.
[src:golang/context] Use context Values only for request-scoped data that transits processes and APIs, not for passing optional parameters to functions.
[src:golang/context] The same Context may be passed to functions running in different goroutines; Contexts are safe for simultaneous use by multiple goroutines.
[src:golang/context] See https://go.dev/blog/context for example code for a server that uses Contexts.
[src:golang/context] Canceled is the error returned by Context.Err when the context is canceled for some reason other than its deadline passing.
[src:golang/context] DeadlineExceeded is the error returned by Context.Err when the context is canceled due to its deadline passing.
[src:golang/context] AfterFunc arranges to call f in its own goroutine after ctx is canceled.
[src:golang/context] If ctx is already canceled, AfterFunc calls f immediately in its own goroutine.
[src:golang/context] Multiple calls to AfterFunc on a context operate independently; one does not replace another.
[src:golang/context] Calling the returned stop function stops the association of ctx with f.
[src:golang/context] It returns true if the call stopped f from being run.
[src:golang/context] If stop returns false, either the context is canceled and f has been started in its own goroutine; or f was already stopped.
[src:golang/context] The stop function does not wait for f to complete before returning.
[src:golang/context] If the caller needs to know whether f is completed, it must coordinate with f explicitly.
[src:golang/context] If ctx has a "AfterFunc(func()) func() bool" method, AfterFunc will use it to schedule the call.
[src:golang/context] This example uses AfterFunc to define a function which waits on a sync.Cond, stopping the wait when a context is canceled.
[src:golang/context] This example uses AfterFunc to define a function which reads from a net.Conn, stopping the read when a context is canceled.
[src:golang/context] This example uses AfterFunc to define a function which combines the cancellation signals of two Contexts.
[src:golang/context] Cause returns a non-nil error explaining why c was canceled.
[src:golang/context] The first cancellation of c or one of its parents sets the cause.
[src:golang/context] If that cancellation happened via a call to CancelCauseFunc(err), then Cause returns err.
[src:golang/context] Otherwise Cause(c) returns the same value as c.Err().
[src:golang/context] Cause returns nil if c has not been canceled yet.
[src:golang/context] WithCancel returns a derived context that points to the parent context but has a new Done channel.
[src:golang/context] The returned context's Done channel is closed when the returned cancel function is called or when the parent context's Done channel is closed, whichever happens first.
[src:golang/context] Canceling this context releases resources associated with it, so code should call cancel as soon as the operations running in this Context complete.
[src:golang/context] This example demonstrates the use of a cancelable context to prevent a goroutine leak.
[src:golang/context] By the end of the example function, the goroutine started by gen will return without leaking.
[src:golang/context] WithCancelCause behaves like WithCancel but returns a CancelCauseFunc instead of a CancelFunc.
[src:golang/context] Calling cancel with a non-nil error (the "cause") records that error in ctx; it can then be retrieved using Cause(ctx).
[src:golang/context] Calling cancel with nil sets the cause to Canceled.
[src:golang/context] WithDeadline returns a derived context that points to the parent context but has the deadline adjusted to be no later than d.
[src:golang/context] If the parent's deadline is already earlier than d, WithDeadline(parent, d) is semantically equivalent to parent.
[src:golang/context] The returned Context.Done channel is closed when the deadline expires, when the returned cancel function is called, or when the parent context's Done channel is closed, whichever happens first.
[src:golang/context] This example passes a context with an arbitrary deadline to tell a blocking function that it should abandon its work as soon as it gets to it.
[src:golang/context] WithDeadlineCause behaves like WithDeadline but also sets the cause of the returned Context when the deadline is exceeded.
[src:golang/context] The returned CancelFunc does not set the cause.
[src:golang/context] WithTimeout returns WithDeadline(parent, time.Now().Add(timeout)).
[src:golang/context] This example passes a context with a timeout to tell a blocking function that it should abandon its work after the timeout elapses.
[src:golang/context] WithTimeoutCause behaves like WithTimeout but also sets the cause of the returned Context when the timeout expires.
[src:golang/context] A CancelCauseFunc behaves like a CancelFunc but additionally sets the cancellation cause.
[src:golang/context] This cause can be retrieved by calling Cause on the canceled Context or on any of its derived Contexts.
[src:golang/context] If the context has already been canceled, CancelCauseFunc does not set the cause.
[src:golang/context] A CancelFunc tells an operation to abandon its work.
[src:golang/context] A CancelFunc does not wait for the work to stop.
[src:golang/context] A CancelFunc may be called by multiple goroutines simultaneously.
[src:golang/context] After the first call, subsequent calls to a CancelFunc do nothing.
[src:golang/context] A Context carries a deadline, a cancellation signal, and other values across API boundaries.
[src:golang/context] Context's methods may be called by multiple goroutines simultaneously.
[src:golang/context] Background returns a non-nil, empty Context.
[src:golang/context] It is never canceled, has no values, and has no deadline.
[src:golang/context] It is typically used by the main function, initialization, and tests, and as the top-level Context for incoming requests.
[src:golang/context] Code should use context.TODO when it's unclear which Context to use or it is not yet available (because the surrounding function has not yet been extended to accept a Context parameter).
[src:golang/context] WithValue returns a derived context that points to the parent Context.
[src:golang/context] In the derived context, the value associated with key is val.
[src:golang/context] The provided key must be comparable and should not be of type string or any other built-in type to avoid collisions between packages using context.
[src:golang/context] Users of WithValue should define their own types for keys.
[src:golang/context] To avoid allocating when assigning to an interface{}, context keys often have concrete type struct{}.
[src:golang/context] Alternatively, exported context key variables' static type should be a pointer or interface.
[src:golang/context] This example demonstrates how a value can be passed to the context and also how to retrieve it if it exists.
[src:golang/context] WithoutCancel returns a derived context that points to the parent context and is not canceled when parent is canceled.
[src:golang/context] The returned context returns no Deadline or Err, and its Done channel is nil.
[src:golang/context] Calling Cause on the returned context returns nil.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This document was written for Go's release in 2009 and is not actively updated.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] While it remains a good guide for using the core language, it does not cover significant changes to the language (generics), ecosystem (modules), or libraries added since.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Go is an open-source programming language that focuses on simplicity, reliability, and efficiency, specifically designed to make it easy to build software at scale.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Although it borrows ideas from existing languages, it has unusual properties that make effective Go programs different in character from programs written in its relatives.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A straightforward translation of a C++ or Java program into Go is unlikely to produce a satisfactory result—Java programs are written in Java, not Go.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] On the other hand, thinking about the problem from a Go perspective could produce a successful but quite different program.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In other words, to write Go well, it's important to understand its properties and idioms.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's also important to know the established conventions for programming in Go, such as naming, formatting, program construction, and so on, so that programs you write will be easy for other Go programmers to understand.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This document gives tips for writing clear, idiomatic Go code.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It augments the language specification, the Tour of Go, and How to Write Go Code, all of which you should read first.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The Go package sources are intended to serve not only as the core library but also as examples of how to use the language.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Moreover, many of the packages contain working, self-contained executable examples you can run directly from the go.dev web site, such as this one (if necessary, click on the word "Example" to open it up).
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you have a question about how to approach a problem or how something might be implemented, the documentation, code and examples in the library can provide answers, ideas and background.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Formatting issues are the most contentious but the least consequential.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] People can adapt to different formatting styles but it's better if they don't have to, and less time is devoted to the topic if everyone adheres to the same style.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The problem is how to approach this Utopia without a long prescriptive style guide.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] With Go we take an unusual approach and let the machine take care of most formatting issues.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The `gofmt` program (also available as `go fmt`, which operates at the package level rather than source file level) reads a Go program and emits the source in a standard style of indentation and vertical alignment, retaining and if necessary reformatting comments.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you want to know how to handle some new layout situation, run `gofmt`; if the answer doesn't seem right, rearrange your program (or file a bug about `gofmt`), don't work around it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] As an example, there's no need to spend time lining up the comments on the fields of a structure.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] All Go code in the standard packages has been formatted with `gofmt`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Don't worry about overflowing a punched card.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If a line feels too long, wrap it and indent with an extra tab.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] ) do not have parentheses in their syntax.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] means what the spacing implies, unlike in the other languages.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Go provides C-style `/* */` block comments and C++-style `//` line comments.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Line comments are the norm; block comments appear mostly as package comments, but are useful within an expression or to disable large swaths of code.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Comments that appear before top-level declarations, with no intervening newlines, are considered to document the declaration itself.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] These “doc comments” are the primary documentation for a given Go package or command.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For more about doc comments, see “Go Doc Comments”.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Names are as important in Go as in any other language.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] They even have semantic effect: the visibility of a name outside a package is determined by whether its first character is upper case.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's therefore worth spending a little time talking about naming conventions in Go programs.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] When a package is imported, the package name becomes an accessor for the contents.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] the importing package can talk about `bytes.Buffer`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's helpful if everyone using the package can use the same name to refer to its contents, which implies that the package name should be good: short, concise, evocative.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] By convention, packages are given lower case, single-word names; there should be no need for underscores or mixedCaps.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Err on the side of brevity, since everyone using your package will be typing that name.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] And don't worry about collisions *a priori*.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The package name is only the default name for imports; it need not be unique across all source code, and in the rare case of a collision the importing package can choose a different name to use locally.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In any case, confusion is rare because the file name in the import determines just which package is being used.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Another convention is that the package name is the base name of its source directory; the package in `src/encoding/base64` is imported as `"encoding/base64"` but has name `base64`, not `encoding_base64` and not `encodingBase64`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The importer of a package will use the name to refer to its contents, so exported names in the package can use that fact to avoid repetition.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Moreover, because imported entities are always addressed with their package name, `bufio.Reader` does not conflict with `io.Reader`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Use the package structure to help you choose good names.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Another short example is `once.Do`; `once.Do(setup)` reads well and would not be improved by writing `once.DoOrWaitUntilDone(setup)`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Long names don't automatically make things more readable.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A helpful doc comment can often be more valuable than an extra long name.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Go doesn't provide automatic support for getters and setters.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There's nothing wrong with providing getters and setters yourself, and it's often appropriate to do so, but it's neither idiomatic nor necessary to put `Get` into the getter's name.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you have a field called `owner` (lower case, unexported), the getter method should be called `Owner` (upper case, exported), not `GetOwner`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The use of upper-case names for export provides the hook to discriminate the field from the method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A setter function, if needed, will likely be called `SetOwner`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] By convention, one-method interfaces are named by the method name plus an -er suffix or similar modification to construct an agent noun: `Reader`, `Writer`, `Formatter`, `CloseNotifier` etc.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There are a number of such names and it's productive to honor them and the function names they capture.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] `Read`, `Write`, `Close`, `Flush`, `String` and so on have canonical signatures and meanings.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To avoid confusion, don't give your method one of those names unless it has the same signature and meaning.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Conversely, if your type implements a method with the same meaning as a method on a well-known type, give it the same name and signature; call your string-converter method `String` not `ToString`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Finally, the convention in Go is to use `MixedCaps` or `mixedCaps` rather than underscores to write multiword names.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Like C, Go's formal grammar uses semicolons to terminate statements, but unlike in C, those semicolons do not appear in the source.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Instead the lexer uses a simple rule to insert semicolons automatically as it scans, so the input text is mostly free of them.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] the lexer always inserts a semicolon after the token.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This could be summarized as, “if the newline comes after a token that could end a statement, insert a semicolon”.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Idiomatic Go programs have semicolons only in places such as `for` loop clauses, to separate the initializer, condition, and continuation elements.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] They are also necessary to separate multiple statements on a line, should you write code that way.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] One consequence of the semicolon insertion rules is that you cannot put the opening brace of a control structure (`if`, `for`, `switch`, or `select`) on the next line.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you do, a semicolon will be inserted before the brace, which could cause unwanted effects.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The control structures of Go are related to those of C but differ in important ways.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The syntax is also slightly different: there are no parentheses and the bodies must always be brace-delimited.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Mandatory braces encourage writing simple `if` statements on multiple lines.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's good style to do so anyway, especially when the body contains a control statement such as a `return` or `break`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Since `if` and `switch` accept an initialization statement, it's common to see one used to set up a local variable.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In the Go libraries, you'll find that when an `if` statement doesn't flow into the next statement—that is, the body ends in `break`, `continue`, `goto`, or `return`—the unnecessary `else` is omitted.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This is an example of a common situation where code must guard against a sequence of error conditions.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The code reads well if the successful flow of control runs down the page, eliminating error cases as they arise.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Since error cases tend to end in `return` statements, the resulting code needs no `else` statements.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] An aside: The last example in the previous section demonstrates a detail of how the `:=` short declaration form works.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This statement declares two variables, `f` and `err`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] which looks as if it declares `d` and `err`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Notice, though, that `err` appears in both statements.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This duplication is legal: `err` is declared by the first statement, but only *re-assigned* in the second.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This means that the call to `f.Stat` uses the existing `err` variable declared above, and just gives it a new value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This unusual property is pure pragmatism, making it easy to use a single `err` value, for example, in a long `if-else` chain.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] § It's worth noting here that in Go the scope of function parameters and return values is the same as the function body, even though they appear lexically outside the braces that enclose the body.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The Go `for` loop is similar to—but not the same as—C's.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It unifies `for` and `while` and there is no `do-while`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There are three forms, only one of which has semicolons.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Short declarations make it easy to declare the index variable right in the loop.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you're looping over an array, slice, string, or map, or reading from a channel, a `range` clause can manage the loop.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The blank identifier has many uses, as described in a later section.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For strings, the `range` does more work for you, breaking out individual Unicode code points by parsing the UTF-8.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Erroneous encodings consume one byte and produce the replacement rune U+FFFD.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] (The name (with associated builtin type) `rune` is Go terminology for a single Unicode code point.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Finally, Go has no comma operator and `++` and `--` are statements not expressions.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Thus if you want to run multiple variables in a `for` you should use parallel assignment (although that precludes `++` and `--`).
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The expressions need not be constants or even integers, the cases are evaluated top to bottom until a match is found, and if the `switch` has no expression it switches on `true`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's therefore possible—and idiomatic—to write an `if`-`else`-`if`-`else` chain as a `switch`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There is no automatic fall through, but cases can be presented in comma-separated lists.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Although they are not nearly as common in Go as some other C-like languages, `break` statements can be used to terminate a `switch` early.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Sometimes, though, it's necessary to break out of a surrounding loop, not the switch, and in Go that can be accomplished by putting a label on the loop and "breaking" to that label.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Of course, the `continue` statement also accepts an optional label but it applies only to loops.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A switch can also be used to discover the dynamic type of an interface variable.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Such a *type switch* uses the syntax of a type assertion with the keyword `type` inside the parentheses.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If the switch declares a variable in the expression, the variable will have the corresponding type in each clause.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's also idiomatic to reuse the name in such cases, in effect declaring a new variable with the same name but a different type in each case.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] One of Go's unusual features is that functions and methods can return multiple values.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This form can be used to improve on a couple of clumsy idioms in C programs: in-band error returns such as `-1` for `EOF` and modifying an argument passed by address.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In C, a write error is signaled by a negative count with the error code secreted away in a volatile location.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In Go, `Write` can return a count *and* an error: “Yes, you wrote some bytes but not all of them because you filled the device”.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] and as the documentation says, it returns the number of bytes written and a non-nil `error` when `n` `!=` `len(b)`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This is a common style; see the section on error handling for more examples.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A similar approach obviates the need to pass a pointer to a return value to simulate a reference parameter.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Here's a simple-minded function to grab a number from a position in a byte slice, returning the number and the next position.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The return or result "parameters" of a Go function can be given names and used as regular variables, just like the incoming parameters.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] When named, they are initialized to the zero values for their types when the function begins; if the function executes a `return` statement with no arguments, the current values of the result parameters are used as the returned values.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The names are not mandatory but they can make code shorter and clearer: they're documentation.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If we name the results of `nextInt` it becomes obvious which returned `int` is which.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Because named results are initialized and tied to an unadorned return, they can simplify as well as clarify.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Go's `defer` statement schedules a function call (the *deferred* function) to be run immediately before the function executing the `defer` returns.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's an unusual but effective way to deal with situations such as resources that must be released regardless of which path a function takes to return.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The canonical examples are unlocking a mutex or closing a file.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Deferring a call to a function such as `Close` has two advantages.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] First, it guarantees that you will never forget to close the file, a mistake that's easy to make if you later edit the function to add a new return path.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Second, it means that the close sits near the open, which is much clearer than placing it at the end of the function.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The arguments to the deferred function (which include the receiver if the function is a method) are evaluated when the *defer* executes, not when the *call* executes.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Besides avoiding worries about variables changing values as the function executes, this means that a single deferred call site can defer multiple function executions.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Deferred functions are executed in LIFO order, so this code will cause `4 3 2 1 0` to be printed when the function returns.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A more plausible example is a simple way to trace function execution through the program.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] We can do better by exploiting the fact that arguments to deferred functions are evaluated when the `defer` executes.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The tracing routine can set up the argument to the untracing routine.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For programmers accustomed to block-level resource management from other languages, `defer` may seem peculiar, but its most interesting and powerful applications come precisely from the fact that it's not block-based but function-based.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In the section on `panic` and `recover` we'll see another example of its possibilities.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Go has two allocation primitives, the built-in functions `new` and `make`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] They do different things and apply to different types, which can be confusing, but the rules are simple.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's a built-in function that allocates memory, but unlike its namesakes in some other languages it does not *initialize* the memory, it only *zeros* it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] That is, `new(T)` allocates zeroed storage for a new variable of type `T` and returns its address, a value of type `*T`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In Go terminology, it returns a pointer to a newly allocated zero value of type `T`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Starting with Go 1.26, `new` also accepts an (value) expression as an argument, which specifies the initial value of the variable.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For example, `new(int64(300))` allocates a new variable of type `int64`, initialized to 300, and returns its address.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Since the memory returned by `new` is zeroed, it's helpful to arrange when designing your data structures that the zero value of each type can be used without further initialization.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This means a user of the data structure can create one with `new` and get right to work.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For example, the documentation for `bytes.Buffer` states that "the zero value for `Buffer` is an empty buffer ready to use." Similarly, `sync.Mutex` does not have an explicit constructor or `Init` method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Instead, the zero value for a `sync.Mutex` is defined to be an unlocked mutex.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The zero-value-is-useful property works transitively.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Values of type `SyncedBuffer` are also ready to use immediately upon allocation or just declaration.
