[src:golang/effective-go-p01] We can simplify it using a *composite literal*, which is an expression that creates a new instance each time it is evaluated.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Note that, unlike in C, it's perfectly OK to return the address of a local variable; the storage associated with the variable survives after the function returns.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In fact, taking the address of a composite literal allocates a fresh instance each time it is evaluated, so we can combine these last two lines.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The fields of a composite literal are laid out in order and must all be present.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] However, by labeling the elements explicitly as *field*`:`*value* pairs, the initializers can appear in any order, with the missing ones left as their respective zero values.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] As a limiting case, if a composite literal contains no fields at all, it creates a zero value for the type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The expressions `new(File)` and `&File{}` are equivalent.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Composite literals can also be created for arrays, slices, and maps, with the field labels being indices or map keys as appropriate.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In these examples, the initializations work regardless of the values of `Enone`, `Eio`, and `Einval`, as long as they are distinct.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The built-in function `make(T,`*args*`)` serves a purpose different from `new(T)`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It creates slices, maps, and channels only, and it returns an *initialized* (not *zeroed*) value of type `T` (not `*T`).
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The reason for the distinction is that these three types represent, under the covers, references to data structures that must be initialized before use.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A slice, for example, is a three-item descriptor containing a pointer to the data (inside an array), the length, and the capacity, and until those items are initialized, the slice is `nil`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For slices, maps, and channels, `make` initializes the internal data structure and prepares the value for use.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] allocates an array of 100 ints and then creates a slice structure with length 10 and a capacity of 100 pointing at the first 10 elements of the array.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] (When making a slice, the capacity can be omitted; see the section on slices for more information.) In contrast, `new([]int)` returns a pointer to a newly allocated, zeroed slice structure, that is, a pointer to a `nil` slice value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] These examples illustrate the difference between `new` and `make`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Remember that `make` applies only to maps, slices and channels and does not return a pointer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To obtain an explicit pointer allocate with `new` or take the address of a variable explicitly.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Arrays are useful when planning the detailed layout of memory and sometimes can help avoid allocation, but primarily they are a building block for slices, the subject of the next section.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To lay the foundation for that topic, here are a few words about arrays.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There are major differences between the ways arrays work in Go and C.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The value property can be useful but also expensive; if you want C-like behavior and efficiency, you can pass a pointer to the array.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Slices wrap arrays to give a more general, powerful, and convenient interface to sequences of data.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Except for items with explicit dimension such as transformation matrices, most array programming in Go is done with slices rather than simple arrays.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Slices hold references to an underlying array, and if you assign one slice to another, both refer to the same array.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If a function takes a slice argument, changes it makes to the elements of the slice will be visible to the caller, analogous to passing a pointer to the underlying array.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A `Read` function can therefore accept a slice argument rather than a pointer and a count; the length within the slice sets an upper limit of how much data to read.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The method returns the number of bytes read and an error value, if any.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To read into the first 32 bytes of a larger buffer `buf`, *slice* (here used as a verb) the buffer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In fact, leaving efficiency aside for the moment, the following snippet would also read the first 32 bytes of the buffer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The length of a slice may be changed as long as it still fits within the limits of the underlying array; just assign it to a slice of itself.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The *capacity* of a slice, accessible by the built-in function `cap`, reports the maximum length the slice may assume.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Here is a function to append data to a slice.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If the data exceeds the capacity, the slice is reallocated.
