[src:golang/effective-go-p01] We must return the slice afterwards because, although `Append` can modify the elements of `slice`, the slice itself (the run-time data structure holding the pointer, length, and capacity) is passed by value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The idea of appending to a slice is so useful it's captured by the `append` built-in function.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To understand that function's design, though, we need a little more information, so we'll return to it later.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Go's arrays and slices are one-dimensional.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Because slices are variable-length, it is possible to have each inner slice be a different length.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] That can be a common situation, as in our `LinesOfText` example: each line has an independent length.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Sometimes it's necessary to allocate a 2D slice, a situation that can arise when processing scan lines of pixels, for instance.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] One is to allocate each slice independently; the other is to allocate a single array and point the individual slices into it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Which to use depends on your application.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If the slices might grow or shrink, they should be allocated independently to avoid overwriting the next line; if not, it can be more efficient to construct the object with a single allocation.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For reference, here are sketches of the two methods.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Maps are a convenient and powerful built-in data structure that associate values of one type (the *key*) with values of another type (the *element* or *value*).
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The key can be of any type for which the equality operator is defined, such as integers, floating point and complex numbers, strings, pointers, interfaces (as long as the dynamic type supports equality), structs and arrays.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Slices cannot be used as map keys, because equality is not defined on them.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Like slices, maps hold references to an underlying data structure.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you pass a map to a function that changes the contents of the map, the changes will be visible in the caller.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Maps can be constructed using the usual composite literal syntax with colon-separated key-value pairs, so it's easy to build them during initialization.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Assigning and fetching map values looks syntactically just like doing the same for arrays and slices except that the index doesn't need to be an integer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] An attempt to fetch a map value with a key that is not present in the map will return the zero value for the type of the entries in the map.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For instance, if the map contains integers, looking up a non-existent key will return `0`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] A set can be implemented as a map with value type `bool`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Set the map entry to `true` to put the value in the set, and then test it by simple indexing.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Sometimes you need to distinguish a missing entry from a zero value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Is there an entry for `"UTC"` or is that 0 because it's not in the map at all?
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] You can discriminate with a form of multiple assignment.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For obvious reasons this is called the “comma ok” idiom.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In this example, if `tz` is present, `seconds` will be set appropriately and `ok` will be true; if not, `seconds` will be set to zero and `ok` will be false.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To test for presence in the map without worrying about the actual value, you can use the blank identifier (`_`) in place of the usual variable for the value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] To delete a map entry, use the `delete` built-in function, whose arguments are the map and the key to be deleted.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's safe to do this even if the key is already absent from the map.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Formatted printing in Go uses a style similar to C's `printf` family but is richer and more general.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The functions live in the `fmt` package and have capitalized names: `fmt.Printf`, `fmt.Fprintf`, `fmt.Sprintf` and so on.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The string functions (`Sprintf` etc.) return a string rather than filling in a provided buffer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] You don't need to provide a format string.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For each of `Printf`, `Fprintf` and `Sprintf` there is another pair of functions, for instance `Print` and `Println`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] These functions do not take a format string but instead generate a default format for each argument.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The `Println` versions also insert a blank between arguments and append a newline to the output while the `Print` versions add blanks only if the operand on neither side is a string.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In this example each line produces the same output.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The formatted print functions `fmt.Fprint` and friends take as a first argument any object that implements the `io.Writer` interface; the variables `os.Stdout` and `os.Stderr` are familiar instances.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] First, the numeric formats such as `%d` do not take flags for signedness or size; instead, the printing routines use the type of the argument to decide these properties.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you just want the default conversion, such as decimal for integers, you can use the catchall format `%v` (for “value”); the result is exactly what `Print` and `Println` would produce.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Moreover, that format can print *any* value, even arrays, slices, structs, and maps.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Here is a print statement for the time zone map defined in the previous section.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For maps, `Printf` and friends sort the output lexicographically by key.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] When printing a struct, the modified format `%+v` annotates the fields of the structure with their names, and for any value the alternate format `%#v` prints the value in full Go syntax.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] (Note the ampersands.) That quoted string format is also available through `%q` when applied to a value of type `string` or `[]byte`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The alternate format `%#q` will use backquotes instead if possible.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] (The `%q` format also applies to integers and runes, producing a single-quoted rune constant.) Also, `%x` works on strings, byte arrays and byte slices as well as on integers, generating a long hexadecimal string, and with a space in the format (`% x`) it puts spaces between the bytes.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Another handy format is `%T`, which prints the *type* of a value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] If you want to control the default format for a custom type, all that's required is to define a method with the signature `String() string` on the type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] For our simple type `T`, that might look like this.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] (If you need to print *values* of type `T` as well as pointers to `T`, the receiver for `String` must be of value type; this example used a pointer because that's more efficient and idiomatic for struct types.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Our `String` method is able to call `Sprintf` because the print routines are fully reentrant and can be wrapped this way.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There is one important detail to understand about this approach, however: don't construct a `String` method by calling `Sprintf` in a way that will recur into your `String` method indefinitely.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] This can happen if the `Sprintf` call attempts to print the receiver directly as a string, which in turn will invoke the method again.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's a common and easy mistake to make, as this example shows.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It's also easy to fix: convert the argument to the basic string type, which does not have the method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] In the initialization section we'll see another technique that avoids this recursion.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Another printing technique is to pass a print routine's arguments directly to another such routine.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] The signature of `Printf` uses the type `...interface{}` for its final argument to specify that an arbitrary number of parameters (of arbitrary type) can appear after the format.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Within the function `Printf`, `v` acts like a variable of type `[]interface{}` but if it is passed to another variadic function, it acts like a regular list of arguments.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] Here is the implementation of the function `log.Println` we used above.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] It passes its arguments directly to `fmt.Sprintln` for the actual formatting.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] We write `...` after `v` in the nested call to `Sprintln` to tell the compiler to treat `v` as a list of arguments; otherwise it would just pass `v` as a single slice argument.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] There's even more to printing than we've covered here.
[src:golang/effective-go-p01] See the `godoc` documentation for package `fmt` for the details.
