[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Although it doesn't look superficially very different from initialization in C or C++, initialization in Go is more powerful.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Complex structures can be built during initialization and the ordering issues among initialized objects, even among different packages, are handled correctly.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] They are created at compile time, even when defined as locals in functions, and can only be numbers, characters (runes), strings or booleans.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Because of the compile-time restriction, the expressions that define them must be constant expressions, evaluatable by the compiler.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For instance, `1<<3` is a constant expression, while `math.Sin(math.Pi/4)` is not because the function call to `math.Sin` needs to happen at run time.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In Go, enumerated constants are created using the `iota` enumerator.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Since `iota` can be part of an expression and expressions can be implicitly repeated, it is easy to build intricate sets of values.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The ability to attach a method such as `String` to any user-defined type makes it possible for arbitrary values to format themselves automatically for printing.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Although you'll see it most often applied to structs, this technique is also useful for scalar types such as floating-point types like `ByteSize`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Variables can be initialized just like constants but the initializer can be a general expression computed at run time.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Finally, each source file can define its own niladic `init` function to set up whatever state is required.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] (Actually each file can have multiple `init` functions.) And finally means finally: `init` is called after all the variable declarations in the package have evaluated their initializers, and those are evaluated only after all the imported packages have been initialized.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Besides initializations that cannot be expressed as declarations, a common use of `init` functions is to verify or repair correctness of the program state before real execution begins.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] As we saw with `ByteSize`, methods can be defined for any named type (except a pointer or an interface); the receiver does not have to be a struct.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In the discussion of slices above, we wrote an `Append` function.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We can define it as a method on slices instead.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] To do this, we first declare a named type to which we can bind the method, and then make the receiver for the method a value of that type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This still requires the method to return the updated slice.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We can eliminate that clumsiness by redefining the method to take a *pointer* to a `ByteSlice` as its receiver, so the method can overwrite the caller's slice.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] then the type `*ByteSlice` satisfies the standard interface `io.Writer`, which is handy.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We pass the address of a `ByteSlice` because only `*ByteSlice` satisfies `io.Writer`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The rule about pointers vs. values for receivers is that value methods can be invoked on pointers and values, but pointer methods can only be invoked on pointers.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This rule arises because pointer methods can modify the receiver; invoking them on a value would cause the method to receive a copy of the value, so any modifications would be discarded.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The language therefore disallows this mistake.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] When the value is addressable, the language takes care of the common case of invoking a pointer method on a value by inserting the address operator automatically.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In our example, the variable `b` is addressable, so we can call its `Write` method with just `b.Write`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The compiler will rewrite that to `(&b).Write` for us.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] By the way, the idea of using `Write` on a slice of bytes is central to the implementation of `bytes.Buffer`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Interfaces in Go provide a way to specify the behavior of an object: if something can do *this*, then it can be used *here*.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We've seen a couple of simple examples already; custom printers can be implemented by a `String` method while `Fprintf` can generate output to anything with a `Write` method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Interfaces with only one or two methods are common in Go code, and are usually given a name derived from the method, such as `io.Writer` for something that implements `Write`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] A type can implement multiple interfaces.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For instance, a collection can be sorted by the routines in package `sort` if it implements `sort.Interface`, which contains `Len()`, `Less(i, j int) bool`, and `Swap(i, j int)`, and it could also have a custom formatter.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In this contrived example `Sequence` satisfies both.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The `String` method of `Sequence` is recreating the work that `Sprint` already does for slices.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] (It also has complexity O(N²), which is poor.) We can share the effort (and also speed it up) if we convert the `Sequence` to a plain `[]int` before calling `Sprint`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This method is another example of the conversion technique for calling `Sprintf` safely from a `String` method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Because the two types (`Sequence` and `[]int`) are the same if we ignore the type name, it's legal to convert between them.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The conversion doesn't create a new value, it just temporarily acts as though the existing value has a new type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It's an idiom in Go programs to convert the type of an expression to access a different set of methods.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Now, instead of having `Sequence` implement multiple interfaces (sorting and printing), we're using the ability of a data item to be converted to multiple types (`Sequence`, `sort.IntSlice` and `[]int`), each of which does some part of the job.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] That's more unusual in practice but can be effective.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Type switches are a form of conversion: they take an interface and, for each case in the switch, in a sense convert it to the type of that case.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Here's a simplified version of how the code under `fmt.Printf` turns a value into a string using a type switch.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If it's already a string, we want the actual string value held by the interface, while if it has a `String` method we want the result of calling the method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The first case finds a concrete value; the second converts the interface into another interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It's perfectly fine to mix types this way.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] What if there's only one type we care about?
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If we know the value holds a `string` and we just want to extract it?
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] A one-case type switch would do, but so would a *type assertion*.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] A type assertion takes an interface value and extracts from it a value of the specified explicit type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] and the result is a new value with the static type `typeName`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] That type must either be the concrete type held by the interface, or a second interface type that the value can be converted to.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] But if it turns out that the value does not contain a string, the program will crash with a run-time error.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If the type assertion fails, `str` will still exist and be of type string, but it will have the zero value, an empty string.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] As an illustration of the capability, here's an `if`-`else` statement that's equivalent to the type switch that opened this section.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If a type exists only to implement an interface and will never have exported methods beyond that interface, there is no need to export the type itself.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Exporting just the interface makes it clear the value has no interesting behavior beyond what is described in the interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It also avoids the need to repeat the documentation on every instance of a common method.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In such cases, the constructor should return an interface value rather than the implementing type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] As an example, in the hash libraries both `crc32.NewIEEE` and `adler32.New` return the interface type `hash.Hash32`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Substituting the CRC-32 algorithm for Adler-32 in a Go program requires only changing the constructor call; the rest of the code is unaffected by the change of algorithm.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] A similar approach allows the streaming cipher algorithms in the various `crypto` packages to be separated from the block ciphers they chain together.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The `Block` interface in the `crypto/cipher` package specifies the behavior of a block cipher, which provides encryption of a single block of data.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Then, by analogy with the `bufio` package, cipher packages that implement this interface can be used to construct streaming ciphers, represented by the `Stream` interface, without knowing the details of the block encryption.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] `NewCTR` applies not just to one specific encryption algorithm and data source but to any implementation of the `Block` interface and any `Stream`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Because they return interface values, replacing CTR encryption with other encryption modes is a localized change.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The constructor calls must be edited, but because the surrounding code must treat the result only as a `Stream`, it won't notice the difference.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Since almost anything can have methods attached, almost anything can satisfy an interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] One illustrative example is in the `http` package, which defines the `Handler` interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Any object that implements `Handler` can serve HTTP requests.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] `ResponseWriter` is itself an interface that provides access to the methods needed to return the response to the client.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Those methods include the standard `Write` method, so an `http.ResponseWriter` can be used wherever an `io.Writer` can be used.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] `Request` is a struct containing a parsed representation of the request from the client.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For brevity, let's ignore POSTs and assume HTTP requests are always GETs; that simplification does not affect the way the handlers are set up.
