[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Finally, let's say we wanted to present on `/args` the arguments used when invoking the server binary.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It's easy to write a function to print the arguments.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] How do we turn that into an HTTP server?
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We could make `ArgServer` a method of some type whose value we ignore, but there's a cleaner way.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Since we can define a method for any type except pointers and interfaces, we can write a method for a function.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] `HandlerFunc` is a type with a method, `ServeHTTP`, so values of that type can serve HTTP requests.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Look at the implementation of the method: the receiver is a function, `f`, and the method calls `f`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] That may seem odd but it's not that different from, say, the receiver being a channel and the method sending on the channel.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] To make `ArgServer` into an HTTP server, we first modify it to have the right signature.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] `ArgServer` now has the same signature as `HandlerFunc`, so it can be converted to that type to access its methods, just as we converted `Sequence` to `IntSlice` to access `IntSlice.Sort`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] When someone visits the page `/args`, the handler installed at that page has value `ArgServer` and type `HandlerFunc`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The HTTP server will invoke the method `ServeHTTP` of that type, with `ArgServer` as the receiver, which will in turn call `ArgServer` (via the invocation `f(w, req)` inside `HandlerFunc.ServeHTTP`).
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In this section we have made an HTTP server from a struct, an integer, a channel, and a function, all because interfaces are just sets of methods, which can be defined for (almost) any type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We've mentioned the blank identifier a couple of times now, in the context of `for` `range` loops and maps.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The blank identifier can be assigned or declared with any value of any type, with the value discarded harmlessly.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It's a bit like writing to the Unix `/dev/null` file: it represents a write-only value to be used as a place-holder where a variable is needed but the actual value is irrelevant.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It has uses beyond those we've seen already.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The use of a blank identifier in a `for` `range` loop is a special case of a general situation: multiple assignment.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If an assignment requires multiple values on the left side, but one of the values will not be used by the program, a blank identifier on the left-hand-side of the assignment avoids the need to create a dummy variable and makes it clear that the value is to be discarded.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For instance, when calling a function that returns a value and an error, but only the error is important, use the blank identifier to discard the irrelevant value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Occasionally you'll see code that discards the error value in order to ignore the error; this is terrible practice.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Always check error returns; they're provided for a reason.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It is an error to import a package or to declare a variable without using it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Unused imports bloat the program and slow compilation, while a variable that is initialized but not used is at least a wasted computation and perhaps indicative of a larger bug.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] When a program is under active development, however, unused imports and variables often arise and it can be annoying to delete them just to have the compilation proceed, only to have them be needed again later.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The blank identifier provides a workaround.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This half-written program has two unused imports (`fmt` and `io`) and an unused variable (`fd`), so it will not compile, but it would be nice to see if the code so far is correct.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] To silence complaints about the unused imports, use a blank identifier to refer to a symbol from the imported package.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Similarly, assigning the unused variable `fd` to the blank identifier will silence the unused variable error.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This version of the program does compile.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] By convention, the global declarations to silence import errors should come right after the imports and be commented, both to make them easy to find and as a reminder to clean things up later.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] An unused import like `fmt` or `io` in the previous example should eventually be used or removed: blank assignments identify code as a work in progress.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] But sometimes it is useful to import a package only for its side effects, without any explicit use.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For example, during its `init` function, the `net/http/pprof` package registers HTTP handlers that provide debugging information.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] It has an exported API, but most clients need only the handler registration and access the data through a web page.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This form of import makes clear that the package is being imported for its side effects, because there is no other possible use of the package: in this file, it doesn't have a name.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] As we saw in the discussion of interfaces above, a type need not declare explicitly that it implements an interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Instead, a type implements the interface just by implementing the interface's methods.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In practice, most interface conversions are static and therefore checked at compile time.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For example, passing an `*os.File` to a function expecting an `io.Reader` will not compile unless `*os.File` implements the `io.Reader` interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Some interface checks do happen at run-time, though.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] One instance is in the `encoding/json` package, which defines a `Marshaler` interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] When the JSON encoder receives a value that implements that interface, the encoder invokes the value's marshaling method to convert it to JSON instead of doing the standard conversion.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] One place this situation arises is when it is necessary to guarantee within the package implementing the type that it actually satisfies the interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If a type—for example, `json.RawMessage`—needs a custom JSON representation, it should implement `json.Marshaler`, but there are no static conversions that would cause the compiler to verify this automatically.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If the type inadvertently fails to satisfy the interface, the JSON encoder will still work, but will not use the custom implementation.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In this declaration, the assignment involving a conversion of a `*RawMessage` to a `Marshaler` requires that `*RawMessage` implements `Marshaler`, and that property will be checked at compile time.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Should the `json.Marshaler` interface change, this package will no longer compile and we will be on notice that it needs to be updated.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The appearance of the blank identifier in this construct indicates that the declaration exists only for the type checking, not to create a variable.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Don't do this for every type that satisfies an interface, though.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] By convention, such declarations are only used when there are no static conversions already present in the code, which is a rare event.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Go does not provide the typical, type-driven notion of subclassing, but it does have the ability to “borrow” pieces of an implementation by *embedding* types within a struct or interface.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We've mentioned the `io.Reader` and `io.Writer` interfaces before; here are their definitions.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The `io` package also exports several other interfaces that specify objects that can implement several such methods.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] For instance, there is `io.ReadWriter`, an interface containing both `Read` and `Write`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This says just what it looks like: A `ReadWriter` can do what a `Reader` does *and* what a `Writer` does; it is a union of the embedded interfaces.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Only interfaces can be embedded within interfaces.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The same basic idea applies to structs, but with more far-reaching implications.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The `bufio` package has two struct types, `bufio.Reader` and `bufio.Writer`, each of which of course implements the analogous interfaces from package `io`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] And `bufio` also implements a buffered reader/writer, which it does by combining a reader and a writer into one struct using embedding: it lists the types within the struct but does not give them field names.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The embedded elements are pointers to structs and of course must be initialized to point to valid structs before they can be used.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] By embedding the structs directly, we avoid this bookkeeping.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The methods of embedded types come along for free, which means that `bufio.ReadWriter` not only has the methods of `bufio.Reader` and `bufio.Writer`, it also satisfies all three interfaces: `io.Reader`, `io.Writer`, and `io.ReadWriter`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] There's an important way in which embedding differs from subclassing.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] When we embed a type, the methods of that type become methods of the outer type, but when they are invoked the receiver of the method is the inner type, not the outer one.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] In our example, when the `Read` method of a `bufio.ReadWriter` is invoked, it has exactly the same effect as the forwarding method written out above; the receiver is the `reader` field of the `ReadWriter`, not the `ReadWriter` itself.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Embedding can also be a simple convenience.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This example shows an embedded field alongside a regular, named field.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] The `Job` type now has the `Print`, `Printf`, `Println` and other methods of `*log.Logger`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] We could have given the `Logger` a field name, of course, but it's not necessary to do so.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If we need to refer to an embedded field directly, the type name of the field, ignoring the package qualifier, serves as a field name, as it did in the `Read` method of our `ReadWriter` struct.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Here, if we needed to access the `*log.Logger` of a `Job` variable `job`, we would write `job.Logger`, which would be useful if we wanted to refine the methods of `Logger`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Embedding types introduces the problem of name conflicts but the rules to resolve them are simple.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] First, a field or method `X` hides any other item `X` in a more deeply nested part of the type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] If `log.Logger` contained a field or method called `Command`, the `Command` field of `Job` would dominate it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] Second, if the same name appears at the same nesting level, it is usually an error; it would be erroneous to embed `log.Logger` if the `Job` struct contained another field or method called `Logger`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] However, if the duplicate name is never mentioned in the program outside the type definition, it is OK.
[src:golang/effective-go-p02] This qualification provides some protection against changes made to types embedded from outside; there is no problem if a field is added that conflicts with another field in another subtype if neither field is ever used.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Concurrent programming is a large topic and there is space only for some Go-specific highlights here.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Concurrent programming in many environments is made difficult by the subtleties required to implement correct access to shared variables.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Go encourages a different approach in which shared values are passed around on channels and, in fact, never actively shared by separate threads of execution.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Only one goroutine has access to the value at any given time.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Reference counts may be best done by putting a mutex around an integer variable, for instance.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] But as a high-level approach, using channels to control access makes it easier to write clear, correct programs.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] One way to think about this model is to consider a typical single-threaded program running on one CPU.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It has no need for synchronization primitives.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Now run another such instance; it too needs no synchronization.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Now let those two communicate; if the communication is the synchronizer, there's still no need for other synchronization.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Unix pipelines, for example, fit this model perfectly.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Although Go's approach to concurrency originates in Hoare's Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP), it can also be seen as a type-safe generalization of Unix pipes.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] They're called *goroutines* because the existing terms—threads, coroutines, processes, and so on—convey inaccurate connotations.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A goroutine has a simple model: it is a function executing concurrently with other goroutines in the same address space.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It is lightweight, costing little more than the allocation of stack space.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] And the stacks start small, so they are cheap, and grow by allocating (and freeing) heap storage as required.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Goroutines are multiplexed onto multiple OS threads so if one should block, such as while waiting for I/O, others continue to run.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Their design hides many of the complexities of thread creation and management.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Prefix a function or method call with the `go` keyword to run the call in a new goroutine.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] When the call completes, the goroutine exits, silently.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A function literal can be handy in a goroutine invocation.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] In Go, function literals are closures: the implementation makes sure the variables referred to by the function survive as long as they are active.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] These examples aren't too practical because the functions have no way of signaling completion.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Like maps, channels are allocated with `make`, and the resulting value acts as a reference to an underlying data structure.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If an optional integer parameter is provided, it sets the buffer size for the channel.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The default is zero, for an unbuffered or synchronous channel.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Unbuffered channels combine communication—the exchange of a value—with synchronization—guaranteeing that two calculations (goroutines) are in a known state.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] There are lots of nice idioms using channels.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] In the previous section we launched a sort in the background.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A channel can allow the launching goroutine to wait for the sort to complete.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Receivers always block until there is data to receive.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If the channel is unbuffered, the sender blocks until the receiver has received the value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If the channel has a buffer, the sender blocks only until the value has been copied to the buffer; if the buffer is full, this means waiting until some receiver has retrieved a value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A buffered channel can be used like a semaphore, for instance to limit throughput.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] In this example, incoming requests are passed to `handle`, which sends a value into the channel, processes the request, and then receives a value from the channel to ready the “semaphore” for the next consumer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The capacity of the channel buffer limits the number of simultaneous calls to `process`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Once `MaxOutstanding` handlers are executing `process`, any more will block trying to send into the filled channel buffer, until one of the existing handlers finishes and receives from the buffer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] This design has a problem, though: `Serve` creates a new goroutine for every incoming request, even though only `MaxOutstanding` of them can run at any moment.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] As a result, the program can consume unlimited resources if the requests come in too fast.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] (Note that in Go versions before 1.22 this code has a bug: the loop variable is shared across all goroutines.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Another approach that manages resources well is to start a fixed number of `handle` goroutines all reading from the request channel.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The number of goroutines limits the number of simultaneous calls to `process`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] This `Serve` function also accepts a channel on which it will be told to exit; after launching the goroutines it blocks receiving from that channel.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] One of the most important properties of Go is that a channel is a first-class value that can be allocated and passed around like any other.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A common use of this property is to implement safe, parallel demultiplexing.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] In the example in the previous section, `handle` was an idealized handler for a request but we didn't define the type it was handling.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If that type includes a channel on which to reply, each client can provide its own path for the answer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Here's a schematic definition of type `Request`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The client provides a function and its arguments, as well as a channel inside the request object on which to receive the answer.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] On the server side, the handler function is the only thing that changes.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] There's clearly a lot more to do to make it realistic, but this code is a framework for a rate-limited, parallel, non-blocking RPC system, and there's not a mutex in sight.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Another application of these ideas is to parallelize a calculation across multiple CPU cores.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If the calculation can be broken into separate pieces that can execute independently, it can be parallelized, with a channel to signal when each piece completes.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Let's say we have an expensive operation to perform on a vector of items, and that the value of the operation on each item is independent, as in this idealized example.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] We launch the pieces independently in a loop, one per CPU.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] They can complete in any order but it doesn't matter; we just count the completion signals by draining the channel after launching all the goroutines.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Rather than create a constant value for numCPU, we can ask the runtime what value is appropriate.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] There is also a function `runtime.GOMAXPROCS`, which reports (or sets) the user-specified number of cores that a Go program can have running simultaneously.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It defaults to the value of `runtime.NumCPU` but can be overridden by setting the similarly named shell environment variable or by calling the function with a positive number.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Calling it with zero just queries the value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Be sure not to confuse the ideas of concurrency—structuring a program as independently executing components—and parallelism—executing calculations in parallel for efficiency on multiple CPUs.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Although the concurrency features of Go can make some problems easy to structure as parallel computations, Go is a concurrent language, not a parallel one, and not all parallelization problems fit Go's model.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] For a discussion of the distinction, see the talk cited in this blog post.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A leaky buffer The tools of concurrent programming can even make non-concurrent ideas easier to express.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Here's an example abstracted from an RPC package.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The client goroutine loops receiving data from some source, perhaps a network.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] To avoid allocating and freeing buffers, it keeps a free list, and uses a buffered channel to represent it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If the channel is empty, a new buffer gets allocated.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The server's send to `freeList` puts `b` back on the free list unless the list is full, in which case the buffer is dropped on the floor to be reclaimed by the garbage collector.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] (The `default` clauses in the `select` statements execute when no other case is ready, meaning that the `selects` never block.) This implementation builds a leaky bucket free list in just a few lines, relying on the buffered channel and the garbage collector for bookkeeping.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Errors Library routines must often return some sort of error indication to the caller.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] As mentioned earlier, Go's multivalue return makes it easy to return a detailed error description alongside the normal return value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It is good style to use this feature to provide detailed error information.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] For example, as we'll see, `os.Open` doesn't just return a `nil` pointer on failure, it also returns an error value that describes what went wrong.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] By convention, errors have type `error`, a simple built-in interface. type error interface { Error() string } A library writer is free to implement this interface with a richer model under the covers, making it possible not only to see the error but also to provide some context.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] As mentioned, alongside the usual `*os.File` return value, `os.Open` also returns an error value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If the file is opened successfully, the error will be `nil`, but when there is a problem, it will hold an `os.PathError`: // PathError records an error and the operation and // file path that caused it. type PathError struct { Op string // "open", "unlink", etc.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] When feasible, error strings should identify their origin, such as by having a prefix naming the operation or package that generated the error.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] For example, in package `image`, the string representation for a decoding error due to an unknown format is "image: unknown format".
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Callers that care about the precise error details can use a type switch or a type assertion to look for specific errors and extract details.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If it fails, `ok` will be false, and `e` will be `nil`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If it succeeds, `ok` will be true, which means the error was of type `*os.PathError`, and then so is `e`, which we can examine for more information about the error.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Panic The usual way to report an error to a caller is to return an `error` as an extra return value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The canonical `Read` method is a well-known instance; it returns a byte count and an `error`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Sometimes the program simply cannot continue.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] For this purpose, there is a built-in function `panic` that in effect creates a run-time error that will stop the program (but see the next section).
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The function takes a single argument of arbitrary type—often a string—to be printed as the program dies.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If the problem can be masked or worked around, it's always better to let things continue to run rather than taking down the whole program.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If that unwinding reaches the top of the goroutine's stack, the program dies.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] However, it is possible to use the built-in function `recover` to regain control of the goroutine and resume normal execution.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A call to `recover` stops the unwinding and returns the argument passed to `panic`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Because the only code that runs while unwinding is inside deferred functions, `recover` is only useful inside deferred functions.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] There's no need to do anything else in the deferred closure; calling `recover` handles the condition completely.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Because `recover` always returns `nil` unless called directly from a deferred function, deferred code can call library routines that themselves use `panic` and `recover` without failing.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] As an example, the deferred function in `safelyDo` might call a logging function before calling `recover`, and that logging code would run unaffected by the panicking state.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] With our recovery pattern in place, the `do` function (and anything it calls) can get out of any bad situation cleanly by calling `panic`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] We can use that idea to simplify error handling in complex software.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Let's look at an idealized version of a `regexp` package, which reports parsing errors by calling `panic` with a local error type.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It will then check, in the assignment to `err`, that the problem was a parse error by asserting that it has the local type `Error`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If it does not, the type assertion will fail, causing a run-time error that continues the stack unwinding as though nothing had interrupted it.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] This check means that if something unexpected happens, such as an index out of bounds, the code will fail even though we are using `panic` and `recover` to handle parse errors.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] `Parse` turns its internal `panic` calls into `error` values; it does not expose `panics` to its client.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] By the way, this re-panic idiom changes the panic value if an actual error occurs.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] However, both the original and new failures will be presented in the crash report, so the root cause of the problem will still be visible.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Thus this simple re-panic approach is usually sufficient—it's a crash after all—but if you want to display only the original value, you can write a little more code to filter unexpected problems and re-panic with the original error.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] That's left as an exercise for the reader.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] A web server Let's finish with a complete Go program, a web server.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] This one is actually a kind of web re-server.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Google provides a service at `chart.apis.google.com` that does automatic formatting of data into charts and graphs.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It's hard to use interactively, though, because you need to put the data into the URL as a query.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The program here provides a nicer interface to one form of data: given a short piece of text, it calls on the chart server to produce a QR code, a matrix of boxes that encode the text.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] That image can be grabbed with your cell phone's camera and interpreted as, for instance, a URL, saving you typing the URL into the phone's tiny keyboard.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The one flag sets a default HTTP port for our server.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The template variable `templ` is where the fun happens.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] It builds an HTML template that will be executed by the server to display the page; more about that in a moment.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The `main` function parses the flags and, using the mechanism we talked about above, binds the function `QR` to the root path for the server.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Then `http.ListenAndServe` is called to start the server; it blocks while the server runs.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] `QR` just receives the request, which contains form data, and executes the template on the data in the form value named `s`.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The template package `html/template` is powerful; this program just touches on its capabilities.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] In essence, it rewrites a piece of HTML text on the fly by substituting elements derived from data items passed to `templ.Execute`, in this case the form value.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Within the template text (`templateStr`), double-brace-delimited pieces denote template actions.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The piece from `{{if .}}` to `{{end}}` executes only if the value of the current data item, called `.` (dot), is non-empty.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] That is, when the string is empty, this piece of the template is suppressed.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The two snippets `{{.}}` say to show the data presented to the template—the query string—on the web page.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The HTML template package automatically provides appropriate escaping so the text is safe to display.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] The rest of the template string is just the HTML to show when the page loads.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] If this is too quick an explanation, see the documentation for the template package for a more thorough discussion.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] And there you have it: a useful web server in a few lines of code plus some data-driven HTML text.
[src:golang/effective-go-p03] Go is powerful enough to make a lot happen in a few lines.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Package json implements encoding and decoding of JSON as defined in RFC 7159.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The mapping between JSON and Go values is described in the documentation for the Marshal and Unmarshal functions.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The JSON standard (RFC 7159) is lax in its definition of a number of parser behaviors.
[src:golang/encoding-json] As such, many JSON parsers behave differently in various scenarios.
[src:golang/encoding-json] These differences in parsers mean that systems that use multiple independent JSON parser implementations may parse the same JSON object in differing ways.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Systems that rely on a JSON object being parsed consistently for security purposes should be careful to understand the behaviors of this parser, as well as how these behaviors may cause interoperability issues with other parser implementations.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Due to the Go Backwards Compatibility promise (https://go.dev/doc/go1compat) there are a number of behaviors this package exhibits that may cause interopability issues, but cannot be changed.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Compact appends to dst the JSON-encoded src with insignificant space characters elided.
[src:golang/encoding-json] HTMLEscape appends to dst the JSON-encoded src with <, >, &, U+2028 and U+2029 characters inside string literals changed to \u003c, \u003e, \u0026, \u2028, \u2029 so that the JSON will be safe to embed inside HTML <script> tags.
[src:golang/encoding-json] For historical reasons, web browsers don't honor standard HTML escaping within <script> tags, so an alternative JSON encoding must be used.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Indent appends to dst an indented form of the JSON-encoded src.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Each element in a JSON object or array begins on a new, indented line beginning with prefix followed by one or more copies of indent according to the indentation nesting.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The data appended to dst does not begin with the prefix nor any indentation, to make it easier to embed inside other formatted JSON data.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Although leading space characters (space, tab, carriage return, newline) at the beginning of src are dropped, trailing space characters at the end of src are preserved and copied to dst.
[src:golang/encoding-json] For example, if src has no trailing spaces, neither will dst; if src ends in a trailing newline, so will dst.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Marshal traverses the value v recursively.
[src:golang/encoding-json] If an encountered value implements Marshaler and is not a nil pointer, Marshal calls Marshaler.MarshalJSON to produce JSON.
[src:golang/encoding-json] If no Marshaler.MarshalJSON method is present but the value implements encoding.TextMarshaler instead, Marshal calls encoding.TextMarshaler.MarshalText and encodes the result as a JSON string.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The nil pointer exception is not strictly necessary but mimics a similar, necessary exception in the behavior of Unmarshaler.UnmarshalJSON.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Floating point, integer, and Number values encode as JSON numbers.
[src:golang/encoding-json] NaN and +/-Inf values will return an UnsupportedValueError.
[src:golang/encoding-json] String values encode as JSON strings coerced to valid UTF-8, replacing invalid bytes with the Unicode replacement rune.
[src:golang/encoding-json] This replacement can be disabled when using an Encoder, by calling Encoder.SetEscapeHTML(false).
[src:golang/encoding-json] Array and slice values encode as JSON arrays, except that []byte encodes as a base64-encoded string, and a nil slice encodes as the null JSON value.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Each exported struct field becomes a member of the object, using the field name as the object key, unless the field is omitted for one of the reasons given below.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The encoding of each struct field can be customized by the format string stored under the "json" key in the struct field's tag.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The format string gives the name of the field, possibly followed by a comma-separated list of options.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The name may be empty in order to specify options without overriding the default field name.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The "omitempty" option specifies that the field should be omitted from the encoding if the field has an empty value, defined as false, 0, a nil pointer, a nil interface value, and any array, slice, map, or string of length zero.
[src:golang/encoding-json] As a special case, if the field tag is "-", the field is always omitted.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Note that a field with name "-" can still be generated using the tag "-,".
[src:golang/encoding-json] 1) If the field type has an "IsZero() bool" method, that will be used to determine whether the value is zero.
[src:golang/encoding-json] 2) Otherwise, the value is zero if it is the zero value for its type.
[src:golang/encoding-json] If both "omitempty" and "omitzero" are specified, the field will be omitted if the value is either empty or zero (or both).
[src:golang/encoding-json] The "string" option signals that a field is stored as JSON inside a JSON-encoded string.
[src:golang/encoding-json] It applies only to fields of string, floating point, integer, or boolean types.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The key name will be used if it's a non-empty string consisting of only Unicode letters, digits, and ASCII punctuation except quotation marks, backslash, and comma.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Embedded struct fields are usually marshaled as if their inner exported fields were fields in the outer struct, subject to the usual Go visibility rules amended as described in the next paragraph.
[src:golang/encoding-json] An anonymous struct field with a name given in its JSON tag is treated as having that name, rather than being anonymous.
[src:golang/encoding-json] An anonymous struct field of interface type is treated the same as having that type as its name, rather than being anonymous.
[src:golang/encoding-json] The Go visibility rules for struct fields are amended for JSON when deciding which field to marshal or unmarshal.
[src:golang/encoding-json] 1) Of those fields, if any are JSON-tagged, only tagged fields are considered, even if there are multiple untagged fields that would otherwise conflict.
[src:golang/encoding-json] 2) If there is exactly one field (tagged or not according to the first rule), that is selected.
[src:golang/encoding-json] 3) Otherwise there are multiple fields, and all are ignored; no error occurs.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Handling of anonymous struct fields is new in Go 1.1.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Prior to Go 1.1, anonymous struct fields were ignored.
[src:golang/encoding-json] To force ignoring of an anonymous struct field in both current and earlier versions, give the field a JSON tag of "-".
[src:golang/encoding-json] The map's key type must either be a string, an integer type, or implement encoding.TextMarshaler.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Pointer values encode as the value pointed to.
[src:golang/encoding-json] A nil pointer encodes as the null JSON value.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Interface values encode as the value contained in the interface.
[src:golang/encoding-json] A nil interface value encodes as the null JSON value.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Channel, complex, and function values cannot be encoded in JSON.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Attempting to encode such a value causes Marshal to return an UnsupportedTypeError.
[src:golang/encoding-json] JSON cannot represent cyclic data structures and Marshal does not handle them.
[src:golang/encoding-json] Passing cyclic structures to Marshal will result in an error.
