[src:golang/fmt] Package fmt implements formatted I/O with functions analogous to C's printf and scanf.
[src:golang/fmt] The format 'verbs' are derived from C's but are simpler.
[src:golang/fmt] There are four families of printing functions defined by their output destination.
[src:golang/fmt] Print, Println and Printf write to os.Stdout; Sprint, Sprintln and Sprintf return a string; Fprint, Fprintln and Fprintf write to an io.Writer; and Append, Appendln and Appendf append the output to a byte slice.
[src:golang/fmt] The functions within each family do the formatting according to the end of the name.
[src:golang/fmt] Print, Sprint, Fprint and Append use the default format for each argument, adding a space between operands when neither is a string.
[src:golang/fmt] Println, Sprintln, Fprintln and Appendln always add spaces and append a newline.
[src:golang/fmt] Printf, Sprintf, Fprintf and Appendf use a sequence of "verbs" to control the formatting.
[src:golang/fmt] Width is specified by an optional decimal number immediately preceding the verb.
[src:golang/fmt] If absent, the width is whatever is necessary to represent the value.
[src:golang/fmt] Precision is specified after the (optional) width by a period followed by a decimal number.
[src:golang/fmt] If no period is present, a default precision is used.
[src:golang/fmt] A period with no following number specifies a precision of zero.
[src:golang/fmt] Width and precision are measured in units of Unicode code points, that is, runes.
[src:golang/fmt] (This differs from C's printf where the units are always measured in bytes.) Either or both of the flags may be replaced with the character '*', causing their values to be obtained from the next operand (preceding the one to format), which must be of type int.
[src:golang/fmt] For most values, width is the minimum number of runes to output, padding the formatted form with spaces if necessary.
[src:golang/fmt] For strings, byte slices and byte arrays, however, precision limits the length of the input to be formatted (not the size of the output), truncating if necessary.
[src:golang/fmt] Normally it is measured in runes, but for these types when formatted with the %x or %X format it is measured in bytes.
[src:golang/fmt] For floating-point values, width sets the minimum width of the field and precision sets the number of places after the decimal, if appropriate, except that for %g/%G precision sets the maximum number of significant digits (trailing zeros are removed).
[src:golang/fmt] The default precision for %e, %f and %#g is 6; for %g it is the smallest number of digits necessary to identify the value uniquely.
[src:golang/fmt] For complex numbers, the width and precision apply to the two components independently and the result is parenthesized, so %f applied to 1.2+3.4i produces (1.200000+3.400000i).
[src:golang/fmt] When formatting a single integer code point or a rune string (type []rune) with %q, invalid Unicode code points are changed to the Unicode replacement character, U+FFFD, as in strconv.QuoteRune.
[src:golang/fmt] Flags are ignored by verbs that do not expect them.
[src:golang/fmt] For example there is no alternate decimal format, so %#d and %d behave identically.
[src:golang/fmt] For each Printf-like function, there is also a Print function that takes no format and is equivalent to saying %v for every operand.
[src:golang/fmt] Another variant Println inserts blanks between operands and appends a newline.
[src:golang/fmt] Regardless of the verb, if an operand is an interface value, the internal concrete value is used, not the interface itself.
[src:golang/fmt] Except when printed using the verbs %T and %p, special formatting considerations apply for operands that implement certain interfaces.
[src:golang/fmt] If an operand implements the Formatter interface, it will be invoked.
[src:golang/fmt] In this case the interpretation of verbs and flags is controlled by that implementation.
[src:golang/fmt] If the %v verb is used with the # flag (%#v) and the operand implements the GoStringer interface, that will be invoked.
[src:golang/fmt] If an operand implements the error interface, the Error method will be invoked to convert the object to a string, which will then be formatted as required by the verb (if any).
[src:golang/fmt] If an operand implements method String() string, that method will be invoked to convert the object to a string, which will then be formatted as required by the verb (if any).
[src:golang/fmt] For compound operands such as slices and structs, the format applies to the elements of each operand, recursively, not to the operand as a whole.
[src:golang/fmt] Thus %q will quote each element of a slice of strings, and %6.2f will control formatting for each element of a floating-point array.
[src:golang/fmt] However, when printing a byte slice with a string-like verb (%s %q %x %X), it is treated identically to a string, as a single item.
[src:golang/fmt] Infinite recursion can also be triggered by self-referential data structures, such as a slice that contains itself as an element, if that type has a String method.
[src:golang/fmt] Such pathologies are rare, however, and the package does not protect against them.
[src:golang/fmt] When printing a struct, fmt cannot and therefore does not invoke formatting methods such as Error or String on unexported fields.
[src:golang/fmt] In Printf, Sprintf, Fprintf, and Appendf, the default behavior is for each formatting verb to format successive arguments passed in the call.
[src:golang/fmt] However, the notation [n] immediately before the verb indicates that the nth one-indexed argument is to be formatted instead.
[src:golang/fmt] The same notation before a '*' for a width or precision selects the argument index holding the value.
[src:golang/fmt] After processing a bracketed expression [n], subsequent verbs will use arguments n+1, n+2, etc. unless otherwise directed.
[src:golang/fmt] All errors begin with the string "%!" followed sometimes by a single character (the verb) and end with a parenthesized description.
[src:golang/fmt] If an Error or String method triggers a panic when called by a print routine, the fmt package reformats the error message from the panic, decorating it with an indication that it came through the fmt package.
[src:golang/fmt] The %!s just shows the print verb in use when the failure occurred.
[src:golang/fmt] If the panic is caused by a nil receiver to an Error, String, or GoString method, however, the output is the undecorated string, "<nil>".
[src:golang/fmt] An analogous set of functions scans formatted text to yield values.
[src:golang/fmt] Scan, Scanf and Scanln read from os.Stdin; Fscan, Fscanf and Fscanln read from a specified io.Reader; Sscan, Sscanf and Sscanln read from an argument string.
[src:golang/fmt] Scan, Fscan, Sscan treat newlines in the input as spaces.
[src:golang/fmt] Scanln, Fscanln and Sscanln stop scanning at a newline and require that the items be followed by a newline or EOF.
[src:golang/fmt] Scanf, Fscanf, and Sscanf parse the arguments according to a format string, analogous to that of Printf.
[src:golang/fmt] In the text that follows, 'space' means any Unicode whitespace character except newline.
[src:golang/fmt] In the format string, a verb introduced by the % character consumes and parses input; these verbs are described in more detail below.
[src:golang/fmt] A character other than %, space, or newline in the format consumes exactly that input character, which must be present.
[src:golang/fmt] A newline with zero or more spaces before it in the format string consumes zero or more spaces in the input followed by a single newline or the end of the input.
[src:golang/fmt] A space following a newline in the format string consumes zero or more spaces in the input.
[src:golang/fmt] Otherwise, any run of one or more spaces in the format string consumes as many spaces as possible in the input.
[src:golang/fmt] Unless the run of spaces in the format string appears adjacent to a newline, the run must consume at least one space from the input or find the end of the input.
[src:golang/fmt] The handling of spaces and newlines differs from that of C's scanf family: in C, newlines are treated as any other space, and it is never an error when a run of spaces in the format string finds no spaces to consume in the input.
[src:golang/fmt] The verbs behave analogously to those of Printf.
[src:golang/fmt] For example, %x will scan an integer as a hexadecimal number, and %v will scan the default representation format for the value.
[src:golang/fmt] The Printf verbs %p and %T and the flags # and + are not implemented.
[src:golang/fmt] For floating-point and complex values, all valid formatting verbs (%b %e %E %f %F %g %G %x %X and %v) are equivalent and accept both decimal and hexadecimal notation (for example: "2.3e+7", "0x4.5p-8") and digit-separating underscores (for example: "3.14159_26535_89793").
[src:golang/fmt] Input processed by verbs is implicitly space-delimited: the implementation of every verb except %c starts by discarding leading spaces from the remaining input, and the %s verb (and %v reading into a string) stops consuming input at the first space or newline character.
[src:golang/fmt] The familiar base-setting prefixes 0b (binary), 0o and 0 (octal), and 0x (hexadecimal) are accepted when scanning integers without a format or with the %v verb, as are digit-separating underscores.
[src:golang/fmt] Width is interpreted in the input text but there is no syntax for scanning with a precision (no %5.2f, just %5f).
[src:golang/fmt] If width is provided, it applies after leading spaces are trimmed and specifies the maximum number of runes to read to satisfy the verb.
[src:golang/fmt] In all the scanning functions, a carriage return followed immediately by a newline is treated as a plain newline (\r\n means the same as \n).
[src:golang/fmt] In all the scanning functions, if an operand implements method Scan (that is, it implements the Scanner interface) that method will be used to scan the text for that operand.
[src:golang/fmt] Also, if the number of arguments scanned is less than the number of arguments provided, an error is returned.
[src:golang/fmt] All arguments to be scanned must be either pointers to basic types or implementations of the Scanner interface.
[src:golang/fmt] Like Scanf and Fscanf, Sscanf need not consume its entire input.
[src:golang/fmt] There is no way to recover how much of the input string Sscanf used.
[src:golang/fmt] Note: Fscan etc. can read one character (rune) past the input they return, which means that a loop calling a scan routine may skip some of the input.
[src:golang/fmt] This is usually a problem only when there is no space between input values.
[src:golang/fmt] If the reader provided to Fscan implements ReadRune, that method will be used to read characters.
[src:golang/fmt] If the reader also implements UnreadRune, that method will be used to save the character and successive calls will not lose data.
[src:golang/fmt] To attach ReadRune and UnreadRune methods to a reader without that capability, use bufio.NewReader.
[src:golang/fmt] These examples demonstrate the basics of printing using a format string.
[src:golang/fmt] Printf, Sprintf, and Fprintf all take a format string that specifies how to format the subsequent arguments.
[src:golang/fmt] For example, %d (we call that a 'verb') says to print the corresponding argument, which must be an integer (or something containing an integer, such as a slice of ints) in decimal.
[src:golang/fmt] The verb %v ('v' for 'value') always formats the argument in its default form, just how Print or Println would show it.
[src:golang/fmt] The special verb %T ('T' for 'Type') prints the type of the argument rather than its value.
[src:golang/fmt] The examples are not exhaustive; see the package comment for all the details.
[src:golang/fmt] Print, Println, and Printf lay out their arguments differently.
[src:golang/fmt] In this example we can compare their behaviors.
[src:golang/fmt] Println always adds blanks between the items it prints, while Print adds blanks only between non-string arguments and Printf does exactly what it is told.
[src:golang/fmt] Sprint, Sprintln, Sprintf, Fprint, Fprintln, and Fprintf behave the same as their corresponding Print, Println, and Printf functions shown here.
[src:golang/fmt] Append formats using the default formats for its operands, appends the result to the byte slice, and returns the updated slice.
[src:golang/fmt] Spaces are added between operands when neither is a string.
[src:golang/fmt] Appendf formats according to a format specifier, appends the result to the byte slice, and returns the updated slice.
[src:golang/fmt] Appendln formats using the default formats for its operands, appends the result to the byte slice, and returns the updated slice.
[src:golang/fmt] Spaces are always added between operands and a newline is appended.
[src:golang/fmt] Errorf formats according to a format specifier and returns the string as a value that satisfies error.
[src:golang/fmt] If the format specifier includes a %w verb with an error operand, the returned error will implement an Unwrap method returning the operand.
[src:golang/fmt] If there is more than one %w verb, the returned error will implement an Unwrap method returning a []error containing all the %w operands in the order they appear in the arguments.
[src:golang/fmt] It is invalid to supply the %w verb with an operand that does not implement the error interface.
[src:golang/fmt] The %w verb is otherwise a synonym for %v.
[src:golang/fmt] The Errorf function lets us use formatting features to create descriptive error messages.
[src:golang/fmt] FormatString returns a string representing the fully qualified formatting directive captured by the State, followed by the argument verb.
[src:golang/fmt] (State does not itself contain the verb.) The result has a leading percent sign followed by any flags, the width, and the precision.
[src:golang/fmt] Missing flags, width, and precision are omitted.
[src:golang/fmt] This function allows a Formatter to reconstruct the original directive triggering the call to Format.
[src:golang/fmt] Fprint formats using the default formats for its operands and writes to w.
[src:golang/fmt] It returns the number of bytes written and any write error encountered.
[src:golang/fmt] Fprintf formats according to a format specifier and writes to w.
[src:golang/fmt] Fprintln formats using the default formats for its operands and writes to w.
[src:golang/fmt] Fscan scans text read from r, storing successive space-separated values into successive arguments.
[src:golang/fmt] It returns the number of items successfully scanned.
[src:golang/fmt] If that is less than the number of arguments, err will report why.
[src:golang/fmt] Fscanf scans text read from r, storing successive space-separated values into successive arguments as determined by the format.
[src:golang/fmt] It returns the number of items successfully parsed.
[src:golang/fmt] Newlines in the input must match newlines in the format.
[src:golang/fmt] Fscanln is similar to Fscan, but stops scanning at a newline and after the final item there must be a newline or EOF.
[src:golang/fmt] Print formats using the default formats for its operands and writes to standard output.
[src:golang/fmt] Printf formats according to a format specifier and writes to standard output.
[src:golang/fmt] Println formats using the default formats for its operands and writes to standard output.
[src:golang/fmt] Scan scans text read from standard input, storing successive space-separated values into successive arguments.
[src:golang/fmt] Scanf scans text read from standard input, storing successive space-separated values into successive arguments as determined by the format.
[src:golang/fmt] The one exception: the verb %c always scans the next rune in the input, even if it is a space (or tab etc.) or newline.
[src:golang/fmt] Scanln is similar to Scan, but stops scanning at a newline and after the final item there must be a newline or EOF.
[src:golang/fmt] Sprint formats using the default formats for its operands and returns the resulting string.
[src:golang/fmt] Sprintf formats according to a format specifier and returns the resulting string.
[src:golang/fmt] Sprintln formats using the default formats for its operands and returns the resulting string.
[src:golang/fmt] Sscan scans the argument string, storing successive space-separated values into successive arguments.
[src:golang/fmt] Sscanf scans the argument string, storing successive space-separated values into successive arguments as determined by the format.
[src:golang/fmt] Sscanln is similar to Sscan, but stops scanning at a newline and after the final item there must be a newline or EOF.
[src:golang/fmt] Formatter is implemented by any value that has a Format method.
[src:golang/fmt] The implementation controls how State and rune are interpreted, and may call Sprint or Fprint(f) etc. to generate its output.
[src:golang/fmt] GoStringer is implemented by any value that has a GoString method, which defines the Go syntax for that value.
[src:golang/fmt] The GoString method is used to print values passed as an operand to a %#v format.
[src:golang/fmt] ScanState represents the scanner state passed to custom scanners.
[src:golang/fmt] Scanners may do rune-at-a-time scanning or ask the ScanState to discover the next space-delimited token.
[src:golang/fmt] Scanner is implemented by any value that has a Scan method, which scans the input for the representation of a value and stores the result in the receiver, which must be a pointer to be useful.
[src:golang/fmt] The Scan method is called for any argument to Scan, Scanf, or Scanln that implements it.
[src:golang/fmt] State represents the printer state passed to custom formatters.
[src:golang/fmt] It provides access to the io.Writer interface plus information about the flags and options for the operand's format specifier.
[src:golang/fmt] Stringer is implemented by any value that has a String method, which defines the “native” format for that value.
[src:golang/fmt] The String method is used to print values passed as an operand to any format that accepts a string or to an unformatted printer such as Print.
[src:golang/getting-started] In this tutorial, you'll get a brief introduction to Go programming.
[src:golang/getting-started] Just use the Download and install steps.
[src:golang/getting-started] Create a hello directory for your first Go source code.
[src:golang/getting-started] Enable dependency tracking for your code.
[src:golang/getting-started] When your code imports packages contained in other modules, you manage those dependencies through your code's own module.
[src:golang/getting-started] That module is defined by a go.mod file that tracks the modules that provide those packages.
[src:golang/getting-started] That go.mod file stays with your code, including in your source code repository.
[src:golang/getting-started] To enable dependency tracking for your code by creating a go.mod file, run the `go mod init` command, giving it the name of the module your code will be in.
[src:golang/getting-started] In actual development, the module path will typically be the repository location where your source code will be kept.
[src:golang/getting-started] For example, the module path might be `github.com/mymodule`.
[src:golang/getting-started] If you plan to publish your module for others to use, the module path *must* be a location from which Go tools can download your module.
[src:golang/getting-started] For more about naming a module with a module path, see Managing dependencies.
[src:golang/getting-started] For the purposes of this tutorial, just use `example/hello`.
[src:golang/getting-started] In your text editor, create a file hello.go in which to write your code.
[src:golang/getting-started] Paste the following code into your hello.go file and save the file.
[src:golang/getting-started] The `go run` command is one of many `go` commands you'll use to get things done with Go.
[src:golang/getting-started] When you need your code to do something that might have been implemented by someone else, you can look for a package that has functions you can use in your code.
[src:golang/getting-started] In the search results, locate and click on the v1 of the `rsc.io/quote` package (it should be listed with the "Other major versions" of `rsc.io/quote/v4`).
[src:golang/getting-started] In the **Documentation** section, under **Index**, note the list of functions you can call from your code.
[src:golang/getting-started] At the top of this page, note that package `quote` is included in the `rsc.io/quote` module.
[src:golang/getting-started] In your Go code, import the `rsc.io/quote` package and add a call to its `Go` function.
[src:golang/getting-started] Go will add the `quote` module as a requirement, as well as a go.sum file for use in authenticating the module.
[src:golang/getting-started] For more, see Authenticating modules in the Go Modules Reference.
[src:golang/getting-started] Run your code to see the message generated by the function you're calling.
[src:golang/getting-started] Notice that your code calls the `Go` function, printing a clever message about communication.
[src:golang/getting-started] When you ran `go mod tidy`, it located and downloaded the `rsc.io/quote` module that contains the package you imported.
[src:golang/getting-started] By default, it downloaded the latest version -- v1.5.2.
[src:golang/getting-started] Don't communicate by sharing memory, share memory by communicating.
[src:golang/getting-started] With this quick introduction, you got Go installed and learned some of the basics.
[src:golang/getting-started] To write some more code with another tutorial, take a look at Create a Go module.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Package http provides HTTP client and server implementations.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Clients and Transports are safe for concurrent use by multiple goroutines and for efficiency should only be created once and re-used.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ListenAndServe starts an HTTP server with a given address and handler.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The handler is usually nil, which means to use DefaultServeMux.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The http package has transparent support for the HTTP/2 protocol.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Server and DefaultTransport automatically enable HTTP/2 support when using HTTPS.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Transport does not enable HTTP/2 by default.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To enable or disable support for HTTP/1, HTTP/2, and/or unencrypted HTTP/2, see the Server.Protocols and Transport.Protocols configuration fields.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To configure advanced HTTP/2 features, see the Server.HTTP2 and Transport.HTTP2 configuration fields.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The "omithttp2" build tag may be used to disable the HTTP/2 implementation contained in the http package.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Unless otherwise noted, these are defined in RFC 7231 section 4.3.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] HTTP status codes as registered with IANA.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] DefaultMaxHeaderBytes is the maximum permitted size of the headers in an HTTP request.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] This can be overridden by setting Server.MaxHeaderBytes.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] DefaultMaxIdleConnsPerHost is the default value of Transport's MaxIdleConnsPerHost.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] TimeFormat is the time format to use when generating times in HTTP headers.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It is like time.RFC1123 but hard-codes GMT as the time zone.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The time being formatted must be in UTC for Format to generate the correct format.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] For parsing this time format, see ParseTime.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] TrailerPrefix is a magic prefix for ResponseWriter.Header map keys that, if present, signals that the map entry is actually for the response trailers, and not the response headers.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The prefix is stripped after the ServeHTTP call finishes and the values are sent in the trailers.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] This mechanism is intended only for trailers that are not known prior to the headers being written.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] DefaultClient is the default Client and is used by Get, Head, and Post.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] DefaultServeMux is the default ServeMux used by Serve.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrAbortHandler is a sentinel panic value to abort a handler.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] While any panic from ServeHTTP aborts the response to the client, panicking with ErrAbortHandler also suppresses logging of a stack trace to the server's error log.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrBodyReadAfterClose is returned when reading a Request or Response Body after the body has been closed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] This typically happens when the body is read after an HTTP Handler calls WriteHeader or Write on its ResponseWriter.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrHandlerTimeout is returned on ResponseWriter Write calls in handlers which have timed out.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrLineTooLong is returned when reading request or response bodies with malformed chunked encoding.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrMissingFile is returned by FormFile when the provided file field name is either not present in the request or not a file field.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrNoCookie is returned by Request's Cookie method when a cookie is not found.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrNoLocation is returned by the Response.Location method when no Location header is present.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrSchemeMismatch is returned when a server returns an HTTP response to an HTTPS client.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrServerClosed is returned by the Server.Serve, ServeTLS, ListenAndServe, and ListenAndServeTLS methods after a call to Server.Shutdown or Server.Close.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrSkipAltProtocol is a sentinel error value defined by Transport.RegisterProtocol.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ErrUseLastResponse can be returned by Client.CheckRedirect hooks to control how redirects are processed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If returned, the next request is not sent and the most recent response is returned with its body unclosed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] NoBody is an io.ReadCloser with no bytes.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Read always returns EOF and Close always returns nil.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It can be used in an outgoing client request to explicitly signal that a request has zero bytes.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] An alternative, however, is to simply set Request.Body to nil.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] CanonicalHeaderKey returns the canonical format of the header key s.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The canonicalization converts the first letter and any letter following a hyphen to upper case; the rest are converted to lowercase.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] For example, the canonical key for "accept-encoding" is "Accept-Encoding".
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If s contains a space or invalid header field bytes, it is returned without modifications.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] DetectContentType implements the algorithm described at https://mimesniff.spec.whatwg.org/ to determine the Content-Type of the given data.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It considers at most the first 512 bytes of data.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] DetectContentType always returns a valid MIME type: if it cannot determine a more specific one, it returns "application/octet-stream".
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Error replies to the request with the specified error message and HTTP code.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It does not otherwise end the request; the caller should ensure no further writes are done to w.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Error deletes the Content-Length header, sets Content-Type to “text/plain; charset=utf-8”, and sets X-Content-Type-Options to “nosniff”.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] This configures the header properly for the error message, in case the caller had set it up expecting a successful output.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Handle registers the handler for the given pattern in DefaultServeMux.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The documentation for ServeMux explains how patterns are matched.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] HandleFunc registers the handler function for the given pattern in DefaultServeMux.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ListenAndServe listens on the TCP network address addr and then calls Serve with handler to handle requests on incoming connections.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Accepted connections are configured to enable TCP keep-alives.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The handler is typically nil, in which case DefaultServeMux is used.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ListenAndServe always returns a non-nil error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ListenAndServeTLS acts identically to ListenAndServe, except that it expects HTTPS connections.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Additionally, files containing a certificate and matching private key for the server must be provided.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the certificate is signed by a certificate authority, the certFile should be the concatenation of the server's certificate, any intermediates, and the CA's certificate.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] MaxBytesReader is similar to io.LimitReader but is intended for limiting the size of incoming request bodies.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] In contrast to io.LimitReader, MaxBytesReader's result is a ReadCloser, returns a non-nil error of type *MaxBytesError for a Read beyond the limit, and closes the underlying reader when its Close method is called.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] MaxBytesReader prevents clients from accidentally or maliciously sending a large request and wasting server resources.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If possible, it tells the ResponseWriter to close the connection after the limit has been reached.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] NotFound replies to the request with an HTTP 404 not found error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ParseHTTPVersion parses an HTTP version string according to RFC 7230, section 2.6.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Note that strings without a minor version, such as "HTTP/2", are not valid.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ParseTime parses a time header (such as the Date: header), trying each of the three formats allowed by HTTP/1.1: TimeFormat, time.RFC850, and time.ANSIC.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ProxyFromEnvironment returns the URL of the proxy to use for a given request, as indicated by the environment variables HTTP_PROXY, HTTPS_PROXY and NO_PROXY (or the lowercase versions thereof).
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Requests use the proxy from the environment variable matching their scheme, unless excluded by NO_PROXY.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The environment values may be either a complete URL or a "host[:port]", in which case the "http" scheme is assumed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] An error is returned if the value is a different form.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A nil URL and nil error are returned if no proxy is defined in the environment, or a proxy should not be used for the given request, as defined by NO_PROXY.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] As a special case, if req.URL.Host is "localhost" (with or without a port number), then a nil URL and nil error will be returned.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ProxyURL returns a proxy function (for use in a Transport) that always returns the same URL.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Redirect replies to the request with a redirect to url, which may be a path relative to the request path.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Any non-ASCII characters in url will be percent-encoded, but existing percent encodings will not be changed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The provided code should be in the 3xx range and is usually StatusMovedPermanently, StatusFound or StatusSeeOther.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the Content-Type header has not been set, Redirect sets it to "text/html; charset=utf-8" and writes a small HTML body.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Setting the Content-Type header to any value, including nil, disables that behavior.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Serve accepts incoming HTTP connections on the listener l, creating a new service goroutine for each.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The service goroutines read requests and then call handler to reply to them.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] HTTP/2 support is only enabled if the Listener returns *tls.Conn connections and they were configured with "h2" in the TLS Config.NextProtos.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ServeContent replies to the request using the content in the provided ReadSeeker.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The main benefit of ServeContent over io.Copy is that it handles Range requests properly, sets the MIME type, and handles If-Match, If-Unmodified-Since, If-None-Match, If-Modified-Since, and If-Range requests.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the response's Content-Type header is not set, ServeContent first tries to deduce the type from name's file extension and, if that fails, falls back to reading the first block of the content and passing it to DetectContentType.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The name is otherwise unused; in particular it can be empty and is never sent in the response.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If modtime is not the zero time or Unix epoch, ServeContent includes it in a Last-Modified header in the response.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the request includes an If-Modified-Since header, ServeContent uses modtime to decide whether the content needs to be sent at all.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The content's Seek method must work: ServeContent uses a seek to the end of the content to determine its size.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Note that *os.File implements the io.ReadSeeker interface.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the caller has set w's ETag header formatted per RFC 7232, section 2.3, ServeContent uses it to handle requests using If-Match, If-None-Match, or If-Range.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If an error occurs when serving the request (for example, when handling an invalid range request), ServeContent responds with an error message.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] By default, ServeContent strips the Cache-Control, Content-Encoding, ETag, and Last-Modified headers from error responses.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The GODEBUG setting httpservecontentkeepheaders=1 causes ServeContent to preserve these headers.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ServeFile replies to the request with the contents of the named file or directory.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the provided file or directory name is a relative path, it is interpreted relative to the current directory and may ascend to parent directories.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the provided name is constructed from user input, it should be sanitized before calling ServeFile.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] As a precaution, ServeFile will reject requests where r.URL.Path contains a ".." path element; this protects against callers who might unsafely use filepath.Join on r.URL.Path without sanitizing it and then use that filepath.Join result as the name argument.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] As another special case, ServeFile redirects any request where r.URL.Path ends in "/index.html" to the same path, without the final "index.html".
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To avoid such redirects either modify the path or use ServeContent.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Outside of those two special cases, ServeFile does not use r.URL.Path for selecting the file or directory to serve; only the file or directory provided in the name argument is used.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ServeFileFS replies to the request with the contents of the named file or directory from the file system fsys.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The files provided by fsys must implement io.Seeker.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the provided name is constructed from user input, it should be sanitized before calling ServeFileFS.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] As a precaution, ServeFileFS will reject requests where r.URL.Path contains a ".." path element; this protects against callers who might unsafely use filepath.Join on r.URL.Path without sanitizing it and then use that filepath.Join result as the name argument.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] As another special case, ServeFileFS redirects any request where r.URL.Path ends in "/index.html" to the same path, without the final "index.html".
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Outside of those two special cases, ServeFileFS does not use r.URL.Path for selecting the file or directory to serve; only the file or directory provided in the name argument is used.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ServeTLS accepts incoming HTTPS connections on the listener l, creating a new service goroutine for each.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ServeTLS always returns a non-nil error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] SetCookie adds a Set-Cookie header to the provided ResponseWriter's headers.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The provided cookie must have a valid Name.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Invalid cookies may be silently dropped.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] StatusText returns a text for the HTTP status code.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It returns the empty string if the code is unknown.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Its zero value (DefaultClient) is a usable client that uses DefaultTransport.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The Client.Transport typically has internal state (cached TCP connections), so Clients should be reused instead of created as needed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Clients are safe for concurrent use by multiple goroutines.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A Client is higher-level than a RoundTripper (such as Transport) and additionally handles HTTP details such as cookies and redirects.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] CloseIdleConnections closes any connections on its Transport which were previously connected from previous requests but are now sitting idle in a "keep-alive" state.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It does not interrupt any connections currently in use.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If Client.Transport does not have a Client.CloseIdleConnections method then this method does nothing.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Do sends an HTTP request and returns an HTTP response, following policy (such as redirects, cookies, auth) as configured on the client.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] An error is returned if caused by client policy (such as CheckRedirect), or failure to speak HTTP (such as a network connectivity problem).
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A non-2xx status code doesn't cause an error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the returned error is nil, the Response will contain a non-nil Body which the user is expected to close.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the Body is not both read to EOF and closed, the Client's underlying RoundTripper (typically Transport) may not be able to re-use a persistent TCP connection to the server for a subsequent "keep-alive" request.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The request Body, if non-nil, will be closed by the underlying Transport, even on errors.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The Body may be closed asynchronously after Do returns.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A non-nil Response with a non-nil error only occurs when CheckRedirect fails, and even then the returned Response.Body is already closed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Generally Get, Post, or PostForm will be used instead of Do.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the server replies with a redirect, the Client first uses the CheckRedirect function to determine whether the redirect should be followed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If permitted, a 301, 302, or 303 redirect causes subsequent requests to use HTTP method GET (or HEAD if the original request was HEAD), with no body.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A 307 or 308 redirect preserves the original HTTP method and body, provided that the Request.GetBody function is defined.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The NewRequest function automatically sets GetBody for common standard library body types.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Any returned error will be of type *url.Error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The url.Error value's Timeout method will report true if the request timed out.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] An error is returned if the Client.CheckRedirect function fails or if there was an HTTP protocol error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A non-2xx response doesn't cause an error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] When err is nil, resp always contains a non-nil resp.Body.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Caller should close resp.Body when done reading from it.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To make a request with custom headers, use NewRequest and Client.Do.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To make a request with a specified context.Context, use NewRequestWithContext and Client.Do.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Head issues a HEAD to the specified URL.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Post issues a POST to the specified URL.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the provided body is an io.Closer, it is closed after the request.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To set custom headers, use NewRequest and Client.Do.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] See the Client.Do method documentation for details on how redirects are handled.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] PostForm issues a POST to the specified URL, with data's keys and values URL-encoded as the request body.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The Content-Type header is set to application/x-www-form-urlencoded.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] To set other headers, use NewRequest and Client.Do.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A ClientConn is a client connection to an HTTP server.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Unlike a Transport, a ClientConn represents a single connection.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Most users should use a Transport rather than creating client connections directly.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Available reports the number of requests that may be sent to the connection without blocking.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It returns 0 if the connection is closed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Outstanding RoundTrip calls are interrupted.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Err reports any fatal connection errors.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It returns nil if the connection is usable.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If it returns non-nil, the connection can no longer be used.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] InFlight reports the number of requests in flight, including reserved requests.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Release releases an unused concurrency slot reserved by Reserve.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If there are no reserved concurrency slots, it has no effect.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Reserve reserves a concurrency slot on the connection.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If Reserve returns nil, one additional RoundTrip call may be made without waiting for an existing request to complete.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The reserved concurrency slot is accounted as an in-flight request.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A successful call to RoundTrip will decrement the Available count and increment the InFlight count.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Each successful call to Reserve should be followed by exactly one call to RoundTrip or Release, which will consume or release the reservation.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the connection is closed or at its concurrency limit, Reserve returns an error.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] RoundTrip implements the RoundTripper interface.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The request is sent on the client connection, regardless of the URL being requested or any proxy settings.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the connection is at its concurrency limit, RoundTrip waits for the connection to become available before sending the request.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] SetStateHook arranges for f to be called when the state of the connection changes.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] At most one call to f is made at a time.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If the connection's state has changed since it was created, f is called immediately in a separate goroutine. f may be called synchronously from RoundTrip or Response.Body.Close.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If SetStateHook is called multiple times, the new hook replaces the old one.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If f is nil, no further calls will be made to f after SetStateHook returns.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] f is called when Available increases (more requests may be sent on the connection), InFlight decreases (existing requests complete), or Err begins returning non-nil (the connection is no longer usable).
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The CloseNotifier interface is implemented by ResponseWriters which allow detecting when the underlying connection has gone away.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] This mechanism can be used to cancel long operations on the server if the client has disconnected before the response is ready.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Deprecated: the CloseNotifier interface predates Go's context package.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] New code should use Request.Context instead.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A ConnState represents the state of a client connection to a server.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It's used by the optional Server.ConnState hook.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A Cookie represents an HTTP cookie as sent in the Set-Cookie header of an HTTP response or the Cookie header of an HTTP request.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] See https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6265 for details.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ParseCookie parses a Cookie header value and returns all the cookies which were set in it.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Since the same cookie name can appear multiple times the returned Values can contain more than one value for a given key.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] ParseSetCookie parses a Set-Cookie header value and returns a cookie.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] String returns the serialization of the cookie for use in a Cookie header (if only Name and Value are set) or a Set-Cookie response header (if other fields are set).
[src:golang/net-http-p01] If c is nil or c.Name is invalid, the empty string is returned.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Valid reports whether the cookie is valid.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] A CookieJar manages storage and use of cookies in HTTP requests.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Implementations of CookieJar must be safe for concurrent use by multiple goroutines.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The net/http/cookiejar package provides a CookieJar implementation.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] CrossOriginProtection implements protections against Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) by rejecting non-safe cross-origin browser requests.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Cross-origin requests are currently detected with the Sec-Fetch-Site header, available in all browsers since 2023, or by comparing the hostname of the Origin header with the Host header.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The GET, HEAD, and OPTIONS methods are safe methods and are always allowed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] It's important that applications do not perform any state changing actions due to requests with safe methods.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] Requests without Sec-Fetch-Site or Origin headers are currently assumed to be either same-origin or non-browser requests, and are allowed.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] The zero value of CrossOriginProtection is valid and has no trusted origins or bypass patterns.
[src:golang/net-http-p01] NewCrossOriginProtection returns a new CrossOriginProtection value.
